<h1>To Jonathan Trumbull, Sr.</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Head Quarters Cambridge 9th M[arc]h 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>The important Post at Dorchester Hill which has long been the object of our particular attention, and which, for various weighty reasons I had delayed<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> taking possession of, I have the pleasure to inform you is now so well secured, that I flatter myself
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0445">[445]</span>
it will not be in the power of the Enemy to dispossess us. A Detachment of twenty five hundred men under the Command of Brigadier General Thomas, on monday evening last begun the Works there, which they have carried on ever since without the least molestation from the EnemyFor two or three nights previous to this, I thought it necessary to draw off their attention from the grand object, and accordingly ordered a brisk Canonade and Bombardment of the Town, which, as I have been since informed, had the desired effect; for they had no suspicion of our real design till Tuesday morning, when they discovered our Troops in possession of the Hill. A Captain of a Transport who made his escape from Boston the night before last informs me, that three thousand men under command of Lord Piercy were ordered to dispossess us, but the weather being very tempestuous (or perhaps for some better reason) the expedition was laid asideHe also informs me, that they were making every necessary preparation to evacuate the Town<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0002-ptr">2</a>They have indeed been observed, for several days past, to be very busily employed in removing their Cannon and Ammunition, and yesterday in the afternoon the Captains intelligence was confirmed by a Flag of Truce sent out with a message from the Select Men of the Town, a copy of which I have the honor to enclose you<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0003-ptr">3</a>It now seems<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> very evident, that they can no longer keep possession of the Town, and are determined to take Post, or attack in some other Quarter. When that may be is, at present, very uncertain;<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> but I thought it my duty to give you the earliest information of this important movement, that you may take proper measures for the security of your own Colony. I have ordered their motions to be very narrowly watched, and if any thing material should occur, you may rely on my giving you speedy notice.</p>
<p>I have also the pleasure to acquaint you, that Captain Manly and others have taken another Transport Ship laden with Coals, Porter &amp;c. for the use of the Ministerial Troops at Boston. She brings Papers to the 2d of December, but they afford no material News.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0006" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0006-ptr">6</a></p>
<p>An armed Transport is also stranded upon the back of Cape Cod; the most of her Cargo, consisting chiefly of a few Military Stores, has been secured by the inhabitants. The Master, two Midshipman and a number of Seamen made Prisoners. She was
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0446">[446]</span>
bound from Boston to New York.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0007" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0007-ptr">7</a> I have the honor to be with great respect Sir your most obedt &amp; very humble Servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go. Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Connecticut State Library, Hartford ]">Ct</span>: Trumbull Papers; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 The letter-book copy in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span> includes the following memorandum: Letters of the same import with the above were sent to His Honor Governor Cooke, To the President of the Assembly of New Hampshire. The letter that Stephen Moylan wrote to the president of the New Hampshire General Court on 9 Mar. is printed in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Nathaniel Bouton, ed. &lt;i&gt;State Papers. Documents and Records Relating to the State of New-Hampshire during the Period of the American Revolution, from 1776 to 1783 . . .&lt;/i&gt;. In &lt;i&gt;New Hampshire Provincial and State Papers&lt;/i&gt;, vol. 8. 1874. Reprint. New York, 1973. ]">Bouton, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">N.H. State Papers</span></span>, 8:8586; a similar one that he wrote to Lord Stirling on this date is in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>. The letter to Cooke has not been found.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span> and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> read had hitherto delayed.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>For a full account of the intelligence brought by Captain Irvine, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0309" class="document">GW to Hancock, 79 Mar. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>See the <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0314" class="document">Boston Selectmen to GW, 8 Mar. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span> and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> omit the word now.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span> and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> read where that may be is at present altogether uncertain.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>For the capture of the ship <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Susannah</span> on 6 Mar., see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0309&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0309-fn-0022#GEWN-03-03-02-0309-fn-0022" class="document">GW to Hancock, 79 Mar. 1776, n.22</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0321-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>For the wreck of the British armed transport <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Friendship</span>, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0309&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0309-fn-0021#GEWN-03-03-02-0309-fn-0021" class="document">GW to Hancock, 79 Mar. 1776, n.21</a>.</p>

